# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: derandomization
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:derandomization/cryptographically-secure-pseudorandom-number-generator] A **cryptographically secure pseudorandom number generator** (**CSPRNG**) or **cryptographic pseudorandom number generator** (**CPRNG**) is a pseudorandom number generator (PRNG) with properties that make it suitable for use in cryptography.
[src:derandomization/cryptographically-secure-pseudorandom-number-generator] It is also referred to as a **cryptographic random number generator** (**CRNG**).
[src:derandomization/cryptographically-secure-pseudorandom-number-generator] The "quality" of the randomness required for these applications varies.
[src:derandomization/cryptographically-secure-pseudorandom-number-generator] For example, creating a nonce in some protocols needs only uniqueness.
[src:derandomization/cryptographically-secure-pseudorandom-number-generator] On the other hand, the generation of a master key requires a higher quality, such as more entropy.
[src:derandomization/cryptographically-secure-pseudorandom-number-generator] And in the case of one-time pads, the information-theoretic guarantee of perfect secrecy only holds if the key material comes from a true random source with high entropy, and thus just any kind of pseudorandom number generator is insufficient.
[src:derandomization/cryptographically-secure-pseudorandom-number-generator] Ideally, the generation of random numbers in CSPRNGs uses entropy obtained from a high-quality source, generally the operating system's randomness API.
[src:derandomization/cryptographically-secure-pseudorandom-number-generator] However, unexpected correlations have been found in several such ostensibly independent processes.
[src:derandomization/cryptographically-secure-pseudorandom-number-generator] From an information-theoretic point of view, the amount of randomness, the entropy that can be generated, is equal to the entropy provided by the system.
[src:derandomization/cryptographically-secure-pseudorandom-number-generator] But sometimes, in practical situations, numbers are needed with more randomness than the available entropy can provide.
[src:derandomization/cryptographically-secure-pseudorandom-number-generator] Also, the processes to extract randomness from a running system are slow in actual practice.
[src:derandomization/cryptographically-secure-pseudorandom-number-generator] In such instances, a CSPRNG can sometimes be used.
[src:derandomization/cryptographically-secure-pseudorandom-number-generator] A CSPRNG can "stretch" the available entropy over more bits.
[src:derandomization/cryptographically-secure-pseudorandom-number-generator] The requirements of an ordinary PRNG are also satisfied by a cryptographically secure PRNG, but the reverse is not true.
[src:derandomization/cryptographically-secure-pseudorandom-number-generator] For most PRNGs, when their state has been revealed, all past random numbers can be retrodicted, allowing an attacker to read all past messages, as well as future ones.
[src:derandomization/cryptographically-secure-pseudorandom-number-generator] CSPRNGs are designed explicitly to resist this type of cryptanalysis.
[src:derandomization/cryptographically-secure-pseudorandom-number-generator] There is an equivalent characterization: For any function family $G_{k}\colon \{{\texttt {0}},{\texttt {1}}\}^{k}\to \{{\texttt {0}},{\texttt {1}}\}^{p(k)}$ , G is a PRNG if and only if the next output bit of G cannot be predicted by a polynomial time algorithm.
[src:derandomization/cryptographically-secure-pseudorandom-number-generator] Any PRNG $G\colon \{{\texttt {0}},{\texttt {1}}\}^{k}\to \{{\texttt {0}},{\texttt {1}}\}^{p(k)}$ can be turned into a forward secure PRNG with block length $p(k)-k$ by splitting its output into the next state and the actual output.
[src:derandomization/cryptographically-secure-pseudorandom-number-generator] This is done by setting $G(s)=G_{\texttt {0}}(s)\Vert G_{\texttt {1}}(s)$ , in which $|G_{\texttt {0}}(s)|=|s|=k$ and $|G_{\texttt {1}}(s)|=p(k)-k$ ; then G is a forward secure PRNG with $G_{\texttt {0}}$ as the next state and $G_{\texttt {1}}$ as the pseudorandom output block of the current period.
[src:derandomization/cryptographically-secure-pseudorandom-number-generator] Santha and Vazirani proved that several bit streams with weak randomness can be combined to produce a higher-quality, quasi-random bit stream.
[src:derandomization/cryptographically-secure-pseudorandom-number-generator] Even earlier, John von Neumann suggested a simple algorithm that can remove a considerable amount of the bias in any bit stream.
[src:derandomization/cryptographically-secure-pseudorandom-number-generator] "Practical" CSPRNG schemes not only include an CSPRNG algorithm, but also a way to initialize ("seed") it while keeping the seed secret.
[src:derandomization/cryptographically-secure-pseudorandom-number-generator] Obviously, the technique is easily generalized to any block cipher; AES has been suggested.
[src:derandomization/cryptographically-secure-pseudorandom-number-generator] If the key *k* is leaked, the entire X9.17 stream can be predicted; this weakness is cited as a reason for creating Yarrow.
[src:derandomization/cryptographically-secure-pseudorandom-number-generator] All these above-mentioned schemes, save for X9.17, also mix the state of a CSPRNG with an additional source of entropy.
[src:derandomization/cryptographically-secure-pseudorandom-number-generator] They are therefore not "pure" pseudorandom number generators, in the sense that the output is not completely determined by their initial state.
[src:derandomization/cryptographically-secure-pseudorandom-number-generator] This addition aims to prevent attacks even if the initial state is compromised.
[src:derandomization/cryptographically-secure-pseudorandom-number-generator] The third PRNG in this standard, CTR DRBG, is based on a block cipher running in counter mode.
[src:derandomization/cryptographically-secure-pseudorandom-number-generator] It has an uncontroversial design but has been proven to be weaker in terms of distinguishing attack, than the security level of the underlying block cipher when the number of bits output from this PRNG is greater than two to the power of the underlying block cipher's block size in bits.
[src:derandomization/cryptographically-secure-pseudorandom-number-generator] When the maximum number of bits output from this PRNG is equal to the 2blocksize, the resulting output delivers the mathematically expected security level that the key size would be expected to generate, but the output is shown to not be indistinguishable from a true random number generator.
[src:derandomization/cryptographically-secure-pseudorandom-number-generator] When the maximum number of bits output from this PRNG is less than it, the expected security level is delivered and the output appears to be indistinguishable from a true random number generator.
[src:derandomization/cryptographically-secure-pseudorandom-number-generator] It is noted in the next revision that the claimed security strength for CTR_DRBG depends on limiting the total number of generate requests and the bits provided per generate request.
[src:derandomization/cryptographically-secure-pseudorandom-number-generator] The fourth and final PRNG in this standard is named Dual EC DRBG.
[src:derandomization/cryptographically-secure-pseudorandom-number-generator] It has been shown to not be cryptographically secure and is believed to have a kleptographic NSA backdoor.
[src:derandomization/cryptographically-secure-pseudorandom-number-generator] This is essentially NIST SP 800-90A with Dual_EC_DRBG removed, and is the withdrawn standard's replacement.
[src:derandomization/cryptographically-secure-pseudorandom-number-generator] During World War II, Japan used a cipher machine for diplomatic communications; the United States was able to crack it and read its messages, mostly because the "key values" used were insufficiently random.
[src:derandomization/k-independent-hashing] Such families allow good average case performance in randomized algorithms or data structures, even if the input data is chosen by an adversary.
[src:derandomization/k-independent-hashing] The trade-offs between the degree of independence and the efficiency of evaluating the hash function are well studied, and many *k*-independent families have been proposed.
[src:derandomization/k-independent-hashing] The goal of hashing is usually to map keys from some large domain (universe) U into a smaller range, such as m bins (labelled ⁠ $[m]=\{0,\dots ,m-1\}$ ⁠).
[src:derandomization/k-independent-hashing] In the analysis of randomized algorithms and data structures, it is often desirable for the hash codes of various keys to "behave randomly".
[src:derandomization/k-independent-hashing] For instance, if the hash code of each key were an independent random choice in ⁠ $[m]$ ⁠, the number of keys per bin could be analyzed using the Chernoff bound.
[src:derandomization/k-independent-hashing] A deterministic hash function cannot offer any such guarantee in an adversarial setting, as the adversary may choose the keys to be the precisely the preimage of a bin.
[src:derandomization/k-independent-hashing] Furthermore, a deterministic hash function does not allow for *rehashing*: sometimes the input data turns out to be bad for the hash function (e.g. there are too many collisions), so one would like to change the hash function.
[src:derandomization/k-independent-hashing] The solution to these problems is to pick a function *randomly* from a large family of hash functions.
[src:derandomization/k-independent-hashing] The randomness in choosing the hash function can be used to guarantee some desired random behavior of the hash codes of any keys of interest.
[src:derandomization/k-independent-hashing] The first definition along these lines was universal hashing, which guarantees a low collision probability for any two designated keys.
[src:derandomization/k-independent-hashing] The concept of ⁠ k ⁠-independent hashing, introduced by Wegman and Carter in 1981, strengthens the guarantees of random behavior to families of k designated keys, and adds a guarantee on the uniform distribution of hash codes.
[src:derandomization/k-independent-hashing] The strictest definition, introduced by Wegman and Carter under the name "strongly universal $_{k}$ hash family", is the following.
[src:derandomization/k-independent-hashing] 2. for any fixed, distinct keys ⁠ $x_{1},\dots ,x_{k}\in U$ ⁠, as h is drawn randomly from ⁠ H ⁠, $h(x_{1}),\dots ,h(x_{k})$ are independent random variables.
[src:derandomization/k-independent-hashing] Often it is inconvenient to achieve the perfect joint probability of $m^{-k}$ due to rounding issues.
[src:derandomization/k-independent-hashing] Observe that, even if $\mu$ is close to ⁠ 1 ⁠, $h(x_{i})$ are no longer independent random variables, which is often a problem in the analysis of randomized algorithms.
[src:derandomization/k-independent-hashing] Therefore, a more common alternative to dealing with rounding issues is to prove that the hash family is close in statistical distance to a k -independent family, which allows black-box use of the independence properties.
[src:derandomization/k-independent-hashing] Given a prime p , one can construct a ⁠ k ⁠-independent hash function $h:\mathbb {Z} _{p}\rightarrow \mathbb {Z} _{p}$ by defining h to be a uniformly random degree- $(k-1)$ polynomial over $\mathbb {Z} _{p}$ .
[src:derandomization/k-independent-hashing] This approach uses $O(k\log p)$ bits of space and allows for an evaluation time of $O(k)$ .
[src:derandomization/k-independent-hashing] There are also constructions that support large k while supporting constant evaluation time.
[src:derandomization/k-independent-hashing] Assuming a polynomial-size universe, Siegel showed that, for any $\epsilon \in (0,1)$ there exists a $\delta \in (0,\epsilon )$ such that a constant-time $n^{\delta }$ -independent hash function can be represented using $O(n^{\epsilon })$ machine words.
[src:derandomization/k-independent-hashing] Subsequent work by Christiani, Pagh, and Thorup achieved an even stronger guarantee: assuming a polynomial-size universe, their construction allows for $n^{\alpha }$ independence using space $n^{\beta }$ , and with constant evaluation time, for any constants $0<\alpha <\beta <1$ .
[src:derandomization/k-independent-hashing] This type of space bound is optimal: any construction that supports k -independence, where $k=\omega (1)$ , and with constant evaluation time, must use space $kn^{\Omega (1)}$ .
[src:derandomization/k-independent-hashing] A construction by Pagh and Pagh gives a guarantee slightly weaker than ⁠ k ⁠-independence, but with essentially ideal space and time bounds.
[src:derandomization/k-independent-hashing] In general the polynomial can be evaluated in any finite field.
[src:derandomization/k-independent-hashing] Besides the fields modulo prime, a popular choice is the field of size ⁠ $2^{n}$ ⁠, which supports fast finite field arithmetic on modern computers.
[src:derandomization/k-independent-hashing] This was the approach taken by Daniel Lemire and Owen Kaser for CLHash.
[src:derandomization/k-independent-hashing] Tabulation hashing is a technique for mapping keys to hash values by partitioning each key into bytes, using each byte as the index into a table of random numbers (with a different table for each byte position), and combining the results of these table lookups by a bitwise exclusive or operation.
[src:derandomization/k-independent-hashing] Thus, it requires more randomness in its initialization than the polynomial method, but avoids possibly slow multiplication operations.
[src:derandomization/k-independent-hashing] It is 3-independent but not 4-independent.
[src:derandomization/k-independent-hashing] Variations of tabulation hashing can achieve higher degrees of independence by performing table lookups based on overlapping combinations of bits from the input key, or by applying simple tabulation hashing iteratively.
[src:derandomization/k-independent-hashing] The notion of ⁠ k ⁠-independence can be used to differentiate between different collision resolution in hashtables, according to the level of independence required to guarantee constant expected time per operation.
[src:derandomization/k-independent-hashing] For instance, hash chaining takes constant expected time even with a **2-independent** family of hash functions, because the expected time to perform a search for a given key is bounded by the expected number of collisions that key is involved in.
[src:derandomization/k-independent-hashing] By linearity of expectation, this expected number equals the sum, over all other keys in the hash table, of the probability that the given key and the other key collide.
[src:derandomization/k-independent-hashing] Because the terms of this sum only involve probabilistic events involving two keys, 2-independence is sufficient to ensure that this sum has the same value that it would for a truly random hash function.
[src:derandomization/k-independent-hashing] Double hashing is another method of hashing that requires a low degree of independence.
[src:derandomization/k-independent-hashing] It is a form of open addressing that uses two hash functions: one to determine the start of a probe sequence, and the other to determine the step size between positions in the probe sequence.
[src:derandomization/k-independent-hashing] As long as both of these are 2-independent, this method gives constant expected time per operation.
[src:derandomization/k-independent-hashing] On the other hand, linear probing, a simpler form of open addressing where the step size is always one can be guaranteed to work in constant expected time per operation with a 5-independent hash function, and there exist 4-independent hash functions for which it takes logarithmic time per operation.
[src:derandomization/k-independent-hashing] For cuckoo hashing the required ⁠ k ⁠-independence is not known as of 2021.
[src:derandomization/k-independent-hashing] In 2009 it was shown that ⁠ $O(\log n)$ ⁠-independence suffices, and **at least 6-independence** is needed.
[src:derandomization/k-independent-hashing] Another approach is to use tabulation hashing, which is not 6-independent, but was shown in 2012 to have other properties sufficient for cuckoo hashing.
[src:derandomization/k-independent-hashing] A third approach from 2014 is to slightly modify the cuckoo hashtable with a so-called stash, which makes it possible to use nothing more than 2-independent hash functions.
[src:derandomization/k-independent-hashing] Kane, Nelson and David Woodruff improved the Flajolet–Martin algorithm for the Distinct Elements Problem in 2010.
[src:derandomization/k-independent-hashing] To give an $\varepsilon$ approximation to the correct answer, they need a **⁠ ${\tfrac {\log 1/\varepsilon }{\log \log 1/\varepsilon }}$ ⁠-independent** hash function.
[src:derandomization/k-independent-hashing] The Count sketch algorithm for dimensionality reduction requires two hash functions, one **2-independent** and one **4-independent**.
[src:derandomization/k-independent-hashing] The Karloff–Zwick algorithm for the MAX-3SAT problem can be implemented with **3-independent** random variables.
[src:derandomization/method-of-conditional-probabilities] In mathematics and computer science, the **method of conditional probabilities** is a systematic method for converting non-constructive probabilistic existence proofs into efficient deterministic algorithms that explicitly construct the desired object.
[src:derandomization/method-of-conditional-probabilities] Often, the probabilistic method is used to prove the existence of mathematical objects with some desired combinatorial properties.
[src:derandomization/method-of-conditional-probabilities] The proofs in that method work by showing that a random object, chosen from some probability distribution, has the desired properties with positive probability.
[src:derandomization/method-of-conditional-probabilities] Consequently, they are nonconstructive — they don't explicitly describe an efficient method for computing the desired objects.
[src:derandomization/method-of-conditional-probabilities] The method of conditional probabilities converts such a proof, in a "very precise sense", into an efficient deterministic algorithm, one that is guaranteed to compute an object with the desired properties.
[src:derandomization/method-of-conditional-probabilities] That is, the method derandomizes the proof.
[src:derandomization/method-of-conditional-probabilities] The basic idea is to replace each random choice in a random experiment by a deterministic choice, so as to keep the conditional probability of failure, given the choices so far, below 1.
[src:derandomization/method-of-conditional-probabilities] The method is particularly relevant in the context of randomized rounding (which uses the probabilistic method to design approximation algorithms).
[src:derandomization/method-of-conditional-probabilities] When applying the method of conditional probabilities, the technical term **pessimistic estimator** refers to a quantity used in place of the true conditional probability (or conditional expectation) underlying the proof.
[src:derandomization/method-of-conditional-probabilities] ... [We then] show that the probabilistic existence proof can be converted, in a very precise sense, into a deterministic approximation algorithm.
[src:derandomization/method-of-conditional-probabilities] Raghavan is discussing the method in the context of randomized rounding, but it works with the probabilistic method in general.
[src:derandomization/method-of-conditional-probabilities] To apply the method to a probabilistic proof, the randomly chosen object in the proof must be choosable by a random experiment that consists of a sequence of "small" random choices.
[src:derandomization/method-of-conditional-probabilities] Here is a trivial example to illustrate the principle.
[src:derandomization/method-of-conditional-probabilities] It is possible to flip three coins so that the number of tails is at least 2.
[src:derandomization/method-of-conditional-probabilities] If the three coins are flipped randomly, the expected number of tails is 1.5.
[src:derandomization/method-of-conditional-probabilities] Thus, there must be some outcome (way of flipping the coins) so that the number of tails is at least 1.5.
[src:derandomization/method-of-conditional-probabilities] Since the number of tails is an integer, in such an outcome there are at least 2 tails.
[src:derandomization/method-of-conditional-probabilities] In this example the random experiment consists of flipping three fair coins.
[src:derandomization/method-of-conditional-probabilities] The experiment is illustrated by the rooted tree in the adjacent diagram.
[src:derandomization/method-of-conditional-probabilities] There are eight outcomes, each corresponding to a leaf in the tree.
[src:derandomization/method-of-conditional-probabilities] A trial of the random experiment corresponds to taking a random walk from the root (the top node in the tree, where no coins have been flipped) to a leaf.
[src:derandomization/method-of-conditional-probabilities] The successful outcomes are those in which at least two coins came up tails.
[src:derandomization/method-of-conditional-probabilities] The interior nodes in the tree correspond to partially determined outcomes, where only 0, 1, or 2 of the coins have been flipped so far.
[src:derandomization/method-of-conditional-probabilities] To apply the method of conditional probabilities, one focuses on the *conditional probability of failure, given the choices so far* as the experiment proceeds step by step.
[src:derandomization/method-of-conditional-probabilities] In the diagram, each node is labeled with this conditional probability.
[src:derandomization/method-of-conditional-probabilities] (For example, if only the first coin has been flipped, and it comes up tails, that corresponds to the second child of the root.
[src:derandomization/method-of-conditional-probabilities] the conditional probability of failure, given the current state, is less than 1.
[src:derandomization/method-of-conditional-probabilities] In this way, it is guaranteed to arrive at a leaf with label 0, that is, a successful outcome.
[src:derandomization/method-of-conditional-probabilities] The invariant holds initially (at the root), because the original proof showed that the (unconditioned) probability of failure is less than 1.
[src:derandomization/method-of-conditional-probabilities] The conditional probability at any interior node is the average of the conditional probabilities of its children.
[src:derandomization/method-of-conditional-probabilities] The latter property is important because it implies that *any interior node whose conditional probability is less than 1 has at least one child whose conditional probability is less than 1.* Thus, from any interior node, one can always choose some child to walk to so as to maintain the invariant.
[src:derandomization/method-of-conditional-probabilities] Since the invariant holds at the end, when the walk arrives at a leaf and all choices have been determined, the outcome reached in this way must be a successful one.
[src:derandomization/method-of-conditional-probabilities] For example, consider the task with coin flipping, but extended to *n* flips for large *n*.
[src:derandomization/method-of-conditional-probabilities] In the ideal case, given a partial state (a node in the tree), the conditional probability of failure (the label on the node) can be efficiently and exactly computed.
[src:derandomization/method-of-conditional-probabilities] (The example above is like this.) If this is so, then the algorithm can select the next node to go to by computing the conditional probabilities at each of the children of the current node, then moving to any child whose conditional probability is less than 1.
[src:derandomization/method-of-conditional-probabilities] As discussed above, there is guaranteed to be such a node.
[src:derandomization/method-of-conditional-probabilities] Unfortunately, in most applications, the conditional probability of failure is not easy to compute efficiently.
[src:derandomization/method-of-conditional-probabilities] Many probabilistic proofs work as follows: they implicitly define a random variable *Q*, show that (i) the expectation of *Q* is at most (or at least) some threshold value, and (ii) in any outcome where *Q* is at most (at least) this threshold, the outcome is a success.
[src:derandomization/method-of-conditional-probabilities] Then (i) implies that there exists an outcome where *Q* is at most (at least) the threshold, and this and (ii) imply that there is a successful outcome.
[src:derandomization/method-of-conditional-probabilities] (In the example above, *Q* is the number of tails, which should be at least the threshold 1.5.
[src:derandomization/method-of-conditional-probabilities] In this case, to keep the conditional probability of failure below 1, it suffices to keep the conditional expectation of *Q* below (or above) the threshold.
[src:derandomization/method-of-conditional-probabilities] In some cases, as a proxy for the exact conditional expectation of the quantity *Q*, one uses an appropriately tight bound called a *pessimistic estimator*.
[src:derandomization/method-of-conditional-probabilities] The pessimistic estimator is a function of the current state.
[src:derandomization/method-of-conditional-probabilities] It should be an upper (or lower) bound for the conditional expectation of *Q* given the current state, and it should be non-increasing (or non-decreasing) in expectation with each random step of the experiment.
[src:derandomization/method-of-conditional-probabilities] Typically, a good pessimistic estimator can be computed by precisely deconstructing the logic of the original proof.
[src:derandomization/method-of-conditional-probabilities] This example demonstrates the method of conditional probabilities using a conditional expectation.
[src:derandomization/method-of-conditional-probabilities] Given any undirected graph *G* = (*V*, *E*), the Max cut problem is to color each vertex of the graph with one of two colors (say black or white) so as to maximize the number of edges whose endpoints have different colors.
[src:derandomization/method-of-conditional-probabilities] To apply the method of conditional probabilities, first model the random experiment as a sequence of small random steps.
[src:derandomization/method-of-conditional-probabilities] In this case it is natural to consider each step to be the choice of color for a particular vertex (so there are |*V*| steps).
[src:derandomization/method-of-conditional-probabilities] Next, replace the random choice at each step by a deterministic choice, so as to keep the conditional probability of failure, given the vertices colored so far, below 1.
[src:derandomization/method-of-conditional-probabilities] In this case, the conditional probability of failure is not easy to calculate.
[src:derandomization/method-of-conditional-probabilities] Indeed, the original proof did not calculate the probability of failure directly; instead, the proof worked by showing that the expected number of cut edges was at least |*E*|/2.
[src:derandomization/method-of-conditional-probabilities] Let random variable *Q* be the number of edges cut.
[src:derandomization/method-of-conditional-probabilities] To keep the conditional probability of failure below 1, it suffices to keep the conditional expectation of *Q* at or above the threshold |*E*|/2.
[src:derandomization/method-of-conditional-probabilities] This is because, as long as the conditional expectation of *Q* is at least |*E*|/2, there must be some still-reachable outcome where *Q* is at least |*E*|/2, so the conditional probability of reaching such an outcome is positive.
[src:derandomization/method-of-conditional-probabilities] To keep the conditional expectation of *Q* at |*E*|/2 or above, the algorithm will, at each step, color the vertex under consideration so as to *maximize* the resulting conditional expectation of *Q*.
[src:derandomization/method-of-conditional-probabilities] This suffices, because there must be some child whose conditional expectation is at least the current state's conditional expectation (and thus at least |*E*|/2).
[src:derandomization/method-of-conditional-probabilities] Given that some of the vertices are colored already, what is this conditional expectation?
[src:derandomization/method-of-conditional-probabilities] The algorithm colors each vertex to maximize the resulting value of the above conditional expectation.
[src:derandomization/method-of-conditional-probabilities] This is guaranteed to keep the conditional expectation at |*E*|/2 or above, and so is guaranteed to keep the conditional probability of failure below 1, which in turn guarantees a successful outcome.
[src:derandomization/method-of-conditional-probabilities] Because of its derivation, this deterministic algorithm is guaranteed to cut at least half the edges of the given graph.
[src:derandomization/method-of-conditional-probabilities] This makes it a 0.5-approximation algorithm for Max-cut.
[src:derandomization/method-of-conditional-probabilities] The next example demonstrates the use of pessimistic estimators.
[src:derandomization/method-of-conditional-probabilities] Clearly the process computes an independent set.
[src:derandomization/method-of-conditional-probabilities] Any vertex *u* that is considered before all of its neighbors will be added to *S*.
[src:derandomization/method-of-conditional-probabilities] Thus, letting *d*(*u*) denote the degree of *u*, the probability that *u* is added to *S* is at least 1/(*d*(*u*)+1).
[src:derandomization/method-of-conditional-probabilities] In this case, the random process has |*V*| steps.
[src:derandomization/method-of-conditional-probabilities] Each step considers some not-yet considered vertex *u* and adds *u* to *S* if none of its neighbors have yet been added.
[src:derandomization/method-of-conditional-probabilities] Let random variable *Q* be the number of vertices added to *S*.
[src:derandomization/method-of-conditional-probabilities] We will replace each random step by a deterministic step that keeps the conditional expectation of *Q* at or above |*V*|/(*D*+1).
[src:derandomization/method-of-conditional-probabilities] This will ensure a successful outcome, that is, one in which the independent set *S* has size at least |*V*|/(*D*+1), realizing the bound in Turán's theorem.
[src:derandomization/method-of-conditional-probabilities] Given that the first t steps have been taken, let *S*(*t*) denote the vertices added so far.
[src:derandomization/method-of-conditional-probabilities] Let *R*(*t*) denote those vertices that have not yet been considered, and that have no neighbors in *S*(*t*).
[src:derandomization/method-of-conditional-probabilities] Let *Q*(*t*) denote the above quantity, which is called a **pessimistic estimator** for the conditional expectation.
[src:derandomization/method-of-conditional-probabilities] The proof showed that the pessimistic estimator is initially at least |*V*|/(*D*+1).
[src:derandomization/method-of-conditional-probabilities] (That is, *Q*(0) ≥ |*V*|/(*D*+1).) The algorithm will make each choice to keep the pessimistic estimator from decreasing, that is, so that *Q*(*t*+1) ≥ *Q*(*t*) for each *t*.
[src:derandomization/method-of-conditional-probabilities] Since the pessimistic estimator is a lower bound on the conditional expectation, this will ensure that the conditional expectation stays above |*V*|/(*D*+1), which in turn will ensure that the conditional probability of failure stays below 1.
[src:derandomization/method-of-conditional-probabilities] Let *u* be the vertex considered by the algorithm in the next ((*t*+1)-st) step.
[src:derandomization/method-of-conditional-probabilities] If *u* already has a neighbor in *S*, then *u* is not added to *S* and (by inspection of *Q*(*t*)), the pessimistic estimator is unchanged.
[src:derandomization/method-of-conditional-probabilities] If *u* does *not* have a neighbor in *S*, then *u* is added to *S*.
[src:derandomization/method-of-conditional-probabilities] Thus, the expected decrease in the sum is at most 1.
[src:derandomization/method-of-conditional-probabilities] Thus, there must exist some choice of *u* that keeps the pessimistic estimator from decreasing.
[src:derandomization/method-of-conditional-probabilities] The algorithm below chooses each vertex *u* to maximize the resulting pessimistic estimator.
[src:derandomization/method-of-conditional-probabilities] By the previous considerations, this keeps the pessimistic estimator from decreasing and guarantees a successful outcome.
[src:derandomization/method-of-conditional-probabilities] Below, *N*(*t*)(*u*) denotes the neighbors of *u* in *R*(*t*) (that is, neighbors of *u* that are neither in *S* nor have a neighbor in *S*).
[src:derandomization/method-of-conditional-probabilities] For the method of conditional probabilities to work, it suffices if the algorithm keeps the pessimistic estimator from decreasing (or increasing, as appropriate).
[src:derandomization/method-of-conditional-probabilities] The algorithm does not necessarily have to maximize (or minimize) the pessimistic estimator.
[src:derandomization/method-of-conditional-probabilities] This gives some flexibility in deriving the algorithm.
[src:derandomization/method-of-conditional-probabilities] The next two algorithms illustrate this.
[src:derandomization/method-of-conditional-probabilities] Each algorithm is analyzed with the same pessimistic estimator as before.
