[src:derandomization/pseudorandom-generator] The random seed itself is typically a short binary string drawn from the uniform distribution.
[src:derandomization/pseudorandom-generator] Many different classes of statistical tests have been considered in the literature, among them the class of all Boolean circuits of a given size.
[src:derandomization/pseudorandom-generator] It is not known whether good pseudorandom generators for this class exist, but it is known that their existence is in a certain sense equivalent to (unproven) circuit lower bounds in computational complexity theory.
[src:derandomization/pseudorandom-generator] Hence the construction of pseudorandom generators for the class of Boolean circuits of a given size rests on currently unproven hardness assumptions.
[src:derandomization/pseudorandom-generator] These functions are the *statistical tests* that the pseudorandom generator will try to fool, and they are usually algorithms.
[src:derandomization/pseudorandom-generator] Sometimes the statistical tests are also called *adversaries* or *distinguishers*.
[src:derandomization/pseudorandom-generator] The notation in the codomain of the functions is the Kleene star.
[src:derandomization/pseudorandom-generator] The quantity $\ell$ is called the *seed length* and the quantity $n-\ell$ is called the *stretch* of the pseudorandom generator.
[src:derandomization/pseudorandom-generator] In most applications, the family ${\mathcal {A}}$ represents some model of computation or some set of algorithms, and one is interested in designing a pseudorandom generator with small seed length and bias, and such that the output of the generator can be computed by the same sort of algorithm.
[src:derandomization/pseudorandom-generator] In cryptography, the class ${\mathcal {A}}$ usually consists of all circuits of size polynomial in the input and with a single bit output, and one is interested in designing pseudorandom generators that are computable by a polynomial-time algorithm and whose bias is negligible in the circuit size.
[src:derandomization/pseudorandom-generator] These pseudorandom generators are sometimes called **cryptographically secure pseudorandom generators (CSPRGs)**.
[src:derandomization/pseudorandom-generator] It is not known if cryptographically secure pseudorandom generators exist.
[src:derandomization/pseudorandom-generator] Proving that they exist is difficult since their existence implies P ≠ NP, which is widely believed but a famously open problem.
[src:derandomization/pseudorandom-generator] The existence of cryptographically secure pseudorandom generators is widely believed.
[src:derandomization/pseudorandom-generator] This is because it has been proven that pseudorandom generators can be constructed from any one-way function which are believed to exist.
[src:derandomization/pseudorandom-generator] Pseudorandom generators are necessary for many applications in cryptography.
[src:derandomization/pseudorandom-generator] The pseudorandom generator theorem shows that cryptographically secure pseudorandom generators exist if and only if one-way functions exist.
[src:derandomization/pseudorandom-generator] Pseudorandom generators have numerous applications in cryptography.
[src:derandomization/pseudorandom-generator] For instance, pseudorandom generators provide an efficient analog of one-time pads.
[src:derandomization/pseudorandom-generator] It is well known that in order to encrypt a message *m* in a way that the cipher text provides no information on the plaintext, the key *k* used must be random over strings of length |m|.
[src:derandomization/pseudorandom-generator] Perfectly secure encryption is very costly in terms of key length.
[src:derandomization/pseudorandom-generator] Key length can be significantly reduced using a pseudorandom generator if perfect security is replaced by semantic security.
[src:derandomization/pseudorandom-generator] Common constructions of stream ciphers are based on pseudorandom generators.
[src:derandomization/pseudorandom-generator] Pseudorandom generators may also be used to construct symmetric key cryptosystems, where a large number of messages can be safely encrypted under the same key.
[src:derandomization/pseudorandom-generator] Such a construction can be based on a pseudorandom function family, which generalizes the notion of a pseudorandom generator.
[src:derandomization/pseudorandom-generator] Then in the 1990s, various idealizations of physics simulations—based on random walks, correlation functions, localization of eigenstates, etc., were used as tests of pseudorandom generators.
[src:derandomization/pseudorandom-generator] NIST announced SP800-22 Randomness tests to test whether a pseudorandom generator produces high quality random bits.
[src:derandomization/pseudorandom-generator] Yongge Wang showed that NIST testing is not enough to detect weak pseudorandom generators and developed statistical distance based testing technique LILtest.
[src:derandomization/pseudorandom-generator] A main application of pseudorandom generators lies in the derandomization of computation that relies on randomness, without corrupting the result of the computation.
[src:derandomization/pseudorandom-generator] Physical computers are deterministic machines, and obtaining true randomness can be a challenge.
[src:derandomization/pseudorandom-generator] Pseudorandom generators can be used to efficiently simulate randomized algorithms with using little or no randomness.
[src:derandomization/pseudorandom-generator] In such applications, the class ${\mathcal {A}}$ describes the randomized algorithm or class of randomized algorithms that one wants to simulate, and the goal is to design an "efficiently computable" pseudorandom generator against ${\mathcal {A}}$ whose seed length is as short as possible.
[src:derandomization/pseudorandom-generator] If a full derandomization is desired, a completely deterministic simulation proceeds by replacing the random input to the randomized algorithm with the pseudorandom string produced by the pseudorandom generator.
[src:derandomization/pseudorandom-generator] The simulation does this for all possible seeds and averages the output of the various runs of the randomized algorithm in a suitable way.
[src:derandomization/pseudorandom-generator] A fundamental question in computational complexity theory is whether all polynomial time randomized algorithms for decision problems can be deterministically simulated in polynomial time.
[src:derandomization/pseudorandom-generator] The existence of such a simulation would imply that **BPP** = **P**.
[src:derandomization/pseudorandom-generator] In 1991, Noam Nisan and Avi Wigderson provided a candidate pseudorandom generator with these properties.
[src:derandomization/pseudorandom-generator] In 1997 Russell Impagliazzo and Avi Wigderson proved that the construction of Nisan and Wigderson is a pseudorandom generator assuming that there exists a decision problem that can be computed in time 2O(*n*) on inputs of length *n* but requires circuits of size 2Ω(*n*).
[src:derandomization/pseudorandom-generator] While unproven assumption about circuit complexity are needed to prove that the Nisan–Wigderson generator works for time-bounded machines, it is natural to restrict the class of statistical tests further such that we need not rely on such unproven assumptions.
[src:derandomization/pseudorandom-generator] One class for which this has been done is the class of machines whose work space is bounded by $O(\log n)$ .
[src:derandomization/pseudorandom-generator] Using a repeated squaring trick known as Savitch's theorem, it is easy to show that every probabilistic log-space computation can be simulated in space $O(\log ^{2}n)$ .
[src:derandomization/pseudorandom-generator] Noam Nisan (1992) showed that this derandomization can actually be achieved with a pseudorandom generator of seed length $O(\log ^{2}n)$ that fools all $O(\log n)$ -space machines.
[src:derandomization/pseudorandom-generator] Nisan's generator has been used by Saks and Zhou (1999) to show that probabilistic log-space computation can be simulated deterministically in space $O(\log ^{1.5}n)$ .
[src:derandomization/pseudorandom-generator] This result was improved by William Hoza in 2021 to space $O(\log ^{1.5}n/{\sqrt {\log \log n}})$ .
[src:derandomization/pseudorandom-generator] When the statistical tests consist of all multivariate linear functions over some finite field $\mathbb {F}$ , one speaks of epsilon-biased generators.
[src:derandomization/pseudorandom-generator] The construction of Naor & Naor (1990) achieves a seed length of $\ell =\log n+O(\log(\epsilon ^{-1}))$ , which is optimal up to constant factors.
[src:derandomization/pseudorandom-generator] Pseudorandom generators for linear functions often serve as a building block for more complicated pseudorandom generators.
[src:derandomization/pseudorandom-generator] Viola (2008) proves that taking the sum of d small-bias generators fools polynomials of degree d .
[src:derandomization/pseudorandom-generator] Constant depth circuits that produce a single output bit.
[src:derandomization/pseudorandom-generator] The pseudorandom generators used in cryptography and universal algorithmic derandomization have not been proven to exist, although their existence is widely believed.
[src:derandomization/pseudorandom-generator] Proofs for their existence would imply proofs of lower bounds on the circuit complexity of certain explicit functions.
[src:derandomization/pseudorandom-generator] Such circuit lower bounds cannot be proved in the framework of natural proofs assuming the existence of stronger variants of cryptographic pseudorandom generators.
[src:derandomization/randomized-algorithm] A **randomized algorithm** is an algorithm that employs a degree of randomness as part of its logic or procedure.
[src:derandomization/randomized-algorithm] In some cases, probabilistic algorithms are the only practical means of solving a problem.
[src:derandomization/randomized-algorithm] As a motivating example, consider the problem of finding an ‘*a*’ in an array of *n* elements.
[src:derandomization/randomized-algorithm] We give two versions of the algorithm, one Las Vegas algorithm and one Monte Carlo algorithm.
[src:derandomization/randomized-algorithm] This algorithm succeeds with probability 1.
[src:derandomization/randomized-algorithm] Since it is constant, the expected run time over many calls is $\Theta (1)$ .
[src:derandomization/randomized-algorithm] If an ‘*a*’ is found, the algorithm succeeds, else the algorithm fails.
[src:derandomization/randomized-algorithm] This algorithm does not guarantee success, but the run time is bounded.
[src:derandomization/randomized-algorithm] The number of iterations is always less than or equal to k.
[src:derandomization/randomized-algorithm] Taking k to be constant the run time (expected and absolute) is $\Theta (1)$ .
[src:derandomization/randomized-algorithm] Randomized algorithms are particularly useful when faced with a malicious "adversary" or attacker who deliberately tries to feed a bad input to the algorithm (see worst-case complexity and competitive analysis (online algorithm)) such as in the Prisoner's dilemma.
[src:derandomization/randomized-algorithm] It is for this reason that randomness is ubiquitous in cryptography.
[src:derandomization/randomized-algorithm] In cryptographic applications, pseudo-random numbers cannot be used, since the adversary can predict them, making the algorithm effectively deterministic.
[src:derandomization/randomized-algorithm] Therefore, either a source of truly random numbers or a cryptographically secure pseudo-random number generator is required.
[src:derandomization/randomized-algorithm] Another area in which randomness is inherent is quantum computing.
[src:derandomization/randomized-algorithm] In the example above, the Las Vegas algorithm always outputs the correct answer, but its running time is a random variable.
[src:derandomization/randomized-algorithm] The Monte Carlo algorithm (related to the Monte Carlo method for simulation) is guaranteed to complete in an amount of time that can be bounded by a function the input size and its parameter *k*, but allows a *small probability of error*.
[src:derandomization/randomized-algorithm] Observe that any Las Vegas algorithm can be converted into a Monte Carlo algorithm (via Markov's inequality), by having it output an arbitrary, possibly incorrect answer if it fails to complete within a specified time.
[src:derandomization/randomized-algorithm] Conversely, if an efficient verification procedure exists to check whether an answer is correct, then a Monte Carlo algorithm can be converted into a Las Vegas algorithm by running the Monte Carlo algorithm repeatedly till a correct answer is obtained.
[src:derandomization/randomized-algorithm] Computational complexity theory models randomized algorithms as *probabilistic Turing machines*.
[src:derandomization/randomized-algorithm] Both Las Vegas and Monte Carlo algorithms are considered, and several complexity classes are studied.
[src:derandomization/randomized-algorithm] Problem classes having (possibly nonterminating) algorithms with polynomial time average case running time whose output is always correct are said to be in ZPP.
[src:derandomization/randomized-algorithm] The class of problems for which both YES and NO-instances are allowed to be identified with some error is called BPP.
[src:derandomization/randomized-algorithm] This class acts as the randomized equivalent of P, i.e.
[src:derandomization/randomized-algorithm] BPP represents the class of efficient randomized algorithms.
[src:derandomization/randomized-algorithm] Quicksort was discovered by Tony Hoare in 1959, and subsequently published in 1961.
[src:derandomization/randomized-algorithm] In the same year, Hoare published the quickselect algorithm, which finds the median element of a list in linear expected time.
[src:derandomization/randomized-algorithm] It remained open until 1973 whether a deterministic linear-time algorithm existed.
[src:derandomization/randomized-algorithm] In 1917, Henry Cabourn Pocklington introduced a randomized algorithm known as Pocklington's algorithm for efficiently finding square roots modulo prime numbers.
[src:derandomization/randomized-algorithm] In 1970, Elwyn Berlekamp introduced a randomized algorithm for efficiently computing the roots of a polynomial over a finite field.
[src:derandomization/randomized-algorithm] Solovay and Volker Strassen discovered a polynomial-time randomized primality test (i.e., determining the primality of a number).
[src:derandomization/randomized-algorithm] Rabin demonstrated that the 1976 Miller's primality test could also be turned into a polynomial-time randomized algorithm.
[src:derandomization/randomized-algorithm] At that time, no provably polynomial-time deterministic algorithms for primality testing were known.
[src:derandomization/randomized-algorithm] One of the earliest randomized data structures is the hash table, which was introduced in 1953 by Hans Peter Luhn at IBM.
[src:derandomization/randomized-algorithm] Luhn's hash table used chaining to resolve collisions and was also one of the first applications of linked lists.
[src:derandomization/randomized-algorithm] Subsequently, in 1954, Gene Amdahl, Elaine M.
[src:derandomization/randomized-algorithm] McGraw, Nathaniel Rochester, and Arthur Samuel of IBM Research introduced linear probing, although Andrey Ershov independently had the same idea in 1957.
[src:derandomization/randomized-algorithm] In 1962, Donald Knuth performed the first correct analysis of linear probing, although the memorandum containing his analysis was not published until much later.
[src:derandomization/randomized-algorithm] The first published analysis was due to Konheim and Weiss in 1966.
[src:derandomization/randomized-algorithm] Early works on hash tables either assumed access to a fully random hash function or assumed that the keys themselves were random.
[src:derandomization/randomized-algorithm] In 1979, Carter and Wegman introduced universal hash functions, which they showed could be used to implement chained hash tables with constant expected time per operation.
[src:derandomization/randomized-algorithm] Early work on randomized data structures also extended beyond hash tables.
[src:derandomization/randomized-algorithm] In 1970, Burton Howard Bloom introduced an approximate-membership data structure known as the Bloom filter.
[src:derandomization/randomized-algorithm] Aragon introduced a randomized balanced search tree known as the treap.
[src:derandomization/randomized-algorithm] In the same year, William Pugh introduced another randomized search tree known as the skip list.
[src:derandomization/randomized-algorithm] Prior to the popularization of randomized algorithms in computer science, Paul Erdős popularized the use of randomized constructions as a mathematical technique for establishing the existence of mathematical objects.
[src:derandomization/randomized-algorithm] This technique has become known as the probabilistic method.
[src:derandomization/randomized-algorithm] Erdős gave his first application of the probabilistic method in 1947, when he used a simple randomized construction to establish the existence of Ramsey graphs.
[src:derandomization/randomized-algorithm] He famously used a more sophisticated randomized algorithm in 1959 to establish the existence of graphs with high girth and chromatic number.
[src:derandomization/randomized-algorithm] Quicksort is a familiar, commonly used algorithm in which randomness can be useful.
[src:derandomization/randomized-algorithm] Many deterministic versions of this algorithm require *O*(*n*2) time to sort *n* numbers for some well-defined class of degenerate inputs (such as an already sorted array), with the specific class of inputs that generate this behavior defined by the protocol for pivot selection.
[src:derandomization/randomized-algorithm] However, if the algorithm selects pivot elements uniformly at random, it has a provably high probability of finishing in *O*(*n* log *n*) time regardless of the characteristics of the input.
[src:derandomization/randomized-algorithm] In computational geometry, a standard technique to build a structure like a convex hull or Delaunay triangulation is to randomly permute the input points and then insert them one by one into the existing structure.
[src:derandomization/randomized-algorithm] The randomization ensures that the expected number of changes to the structure caused by an insertion is small, and so the expected running time of the algorithm can be bounded from above.
[src:derandomization/randomized-algorithm] This technique is known as randomized incremental construction.
[src:derandomization/randomized-algorithm] Recall that the contraction of two nodes, *u* and *v*, in a (multi-)graph yields a new node *u* ' with edges that are the union of the edges incident on either *u* or *v*, except from any edge(s) connecting *u* and *v*.
[src:derandomization/randomized-algorithm] Figure 1 gives an example of contraction of vertex *A* and *B*.
[src:derandomization/randomized-algorithm] After contraction, the resulting graph may have parallel edges, but contains no self loops.
[src:derandomization/randomized-algorithm] In each execution of the outer loop, the algorithm repeats the inner loop until only 2 nodes remain, the corresponding cut is obtained.
[src:derandomization/randomized-algorithm] The run time of one execution is $O(n)$ , and *n* denotes the number of vertices.
[src:derandomization/randomized-algorithm] After *m* times executions of the outer loop, we output the minimum cut among all the results.
[src:derandomization/randomized-algorithm] The figure 2 gives an example of one execution of the algorithm.
[src:derandomization/randomized-algorithm] After execution, we get a cut of size 3.
[src:derandomization/randomized-algorithm] If *G* is not connected, then *G* can be partitioned into *L* and *R* without any edge between them.
[src:derandomization/randomized-algorithm] So the min cut in a disconnected graph is 0.
[src:derandomization/randomized-algorithm] Initially, *u*,*v* are distinct vertices.
[src:derandomization/randomized-algorithm] *As long as we pick an edge ⁠ $f\neq e$ ⁠, u and v do not get merged.* Thus, at the end of the algorithm, we have two compound nodes covering the entire graph, one consisting of the vertices of *L* and the other consisting of the vertices of *R*.
[src:derandomization/randomized-algorithm] As in figure 2, the size of min cut is 1, and *C* = {(*A*,*B*)}.
[src:derandomization/randomized-algorithm] If we don't select (*A*,*B*) for contraction, we can get the min cut.
[src:derandomization/randomized-algorithm] Because the min cut is *k*, every vertex *v* must satisfy degree(*v*) ≥ *k*.
[src:derandomization/randomized-algorithm] Therefore, the sum of the degree is at least *pk*.
[src:derandomization/randomized-algorithm] But it is well known that the sum of vertex degrees equals 2|*E*|.
[src:derandomization/randomized-algorithm] The probability that the algorithm succeeds is 1 − the probability that all attempts fail.
[src:derandomization/randomized-algorithm] By lemma 1, the probability that *C**i* = *C* is the probability that no edge of *C* is selected during iteration *i*.
[src:derandomization/randomized-algorithm] Consider the inner loop and let *G**j* denote the graph after *j* edge contractions, where *j* ∈ {0, 1, …, *n* − 3}.
[src:derandomization/randomized-algorithm] We use the chain rule of conditional possibilities.
[src:derandomization/randomized-algorithm] The probability that the edge chosen at iteration *j* is not in *C*, given that no edge of *C* has been chosen before, is $1-{\frac {k}{|E(G_{j})|}}$ .
[src:derandomization/randomized-algorithm] Note that *G**j* still has min cut of size *k*, so by Lemma 2, it still has at least ${\frac {(n-j)k}{2}}$ edges.
[src:derandomization/randomized-algorithm] Thus the probability that the algorithm succeeds is at least $1-\left(1-{\frac {2}{n(n-1)}}\right)^{m}$ .
[src:derandomization/randomized-algorithm] The algorithm finds the min cut with probability $1-{\frac {1}{n}}$ , in time $O(mn)=O(n^{3}\log n)$ .
[src:derandomization/randomized-algorithm] Randomness can be viewed as a resource, like space and time.
[src:derandomization/randomized-algorithm] Derandomization is then the process of *removing* randomness (or using as little of it as possible).
[src:derandomization/randomized-algorithm] It is not currently known if all algorithms can be derandomized without significantly increasing their running time.
[src:derandomization/randomized-algorithm] For instance, in computational complexity, it is unknown whether P = BPP, i.e., we do not know whether we can take an arbitrary randomized algorithm that runs in polynomial time with a small error probability and derandomize it to run in polynomial time without using randomness.
[src:derandomization/randomized-algorithm] When the model of computation is restricted to Turing machines, it is currently an open question whether the ability to make random choices allows some problems to be solved in polynomial time that cannot be solved in polynomial time without this ability; this is the question of whether P = BPP.
[src:derandomization/randomized-algorithm] However, in other contexts, there are specific examples of problems where randomization yields strict improvements.
[src:derandomization/small-bias-sample-space] In theoretical computer science, a **small-bias sample space** (also known as **$\epsilon$ -biased sample space**, **$\epsilon$ -biased generator**, or **small-bias probability space**) is a probability distribution that fools parity functions.
[src:derandomization/small-bias-sample-space] In other words, no parity function can distinguish between a small-bias sample space and the uniform distribution with high probability, and hence, small-bias sample spaces naturally give rise to pseudorandom generators for parity functions.
[src:derandomization/small-bias-sample-space] The main useful property of small-bias sample spaces is that they need far fewer truly random bits than the uniform distribution to fool parities.
[src:derandomization/small-bias-sample-space] Efficient constructions of small-bias sample spaces have found many applications in computer science, some of which are derandomization, error-correcting codes, and probabilistically checkable proofs.
[src:derandomization/small-bias-sample-space] The connection with error-correcting codes is in fact very strong since $\epsilon$ -biased sample spaces are *equivalent* to **$\epsilon$ -balanced error-correcting codes**.
[src:derandomization/small-bias-sample-space] Let X be a probability distribution over $\{0,1\}^{n}$ .
[src:derandomization/small-bias-sample-space] where the sum is taken over $\mathbb {F} _{2}$ , the finite field with two elements.
[src:derandomization/small-bias-sample-space] In other words, the sum $\sum _{i\in I}x_{i}$ equals 0 if the number of ones in the sample $x\in \{0,1\}^{n}$ at the positions defined by I is even, and otherwise, the sum equals 1 .
[src:derandomization/small-bias-sample-space] For $I=\emptyset$ , the empty sum is defined to be zero, and hence ${\text{bias}}_{\emptyset }(X)=1$ .
[src:derandomization/small-bias-sample-space] A probability distribution X over $\{0,1\}^{n}$ is called an *$\epsilon$ -biased sample space* if ${\text{bias}}_{I}(X)\leq \epsilon$ holds for all non-empty subsets $I\subseteq \{1,2,\ldots ,n\}$ .
[src:derandomization/small-bias-sample-space] An $\epsilon$ -biased sample space X that is generated by picking a uniform element from a multiset $X\subseteq \{0,1\}^{n}$ is called *$\epsilon$ -biased set*.
[src:derandomization/small-bias-sample-space] The *size* s of an $\epsilon$ -biased set X is the size of the multiset that generates the sample space.
[src:derandomization/small-bias-sample-space] An $\epsilon$ -biased generator $G:\{0,1\}^{\ell }\to \{0,1\}^{n}$ is a function that maps strings of length $\ell$ to strings of length n such that the multiset $X_{G}=\{G(y)\;\vert \;y\in \{0,1\}^{\ell }\}$ is an $\epsilon$ -biased set.
[src:derandomization/small-bias-sample-space] The *seed length* of the generator is the number $\ell$ and is related to the size of the $\epsilon$ -biased set $X_{G}$ via the equation $s=2^{\ell }$ .
[src:derandomization/small-bias-sample-space] There is a close connection between $\epsilon$ -biased sets and *$\epsilon$ -balanced* linear error-correcting codes.
[src:derandomization/small-bias-sample-space] A linear code $C:\{0,1\}^{n}\to \{0,1\}^{s}$ of message length n and block length s is *$\epsilon$ -balanced* if the Hamming weight of every nonzero codeword $C(x)$ is between $({\frac {1}{2}}-\epsilon )s$ and $({\frac {1}{2}}+\epsilon )s$ .
[src:derandomization/small-bias-sample-space] Since C is a linear code, its generator matrix is an $(n\times s)$ -matrix A over $\mathbb {F} _{2}$ with $C(x)=x\cdot A$ .
[src:derandomization/small-bias-sample-space] Then it holds that a multiset $X\subset \{0,1\}^{n}$ is $\epsilon$ -biased if and only if the linear code $C_{X}$ , whose columns are exactly elements of X , is $\epsilon$ -balanced.
[src:derandomization/small-bias-sample-space] Usually the goal is to find $\epsilon$ -biased sets that have a small size s relative to the parameters n and $\epsilon$ .
[src:derandomization/small-bias-sample-space] This is because a smaller size s means that the amount of randomness needed to pick a random element from the set is smaller, and so the set can be used to fool parities using few random bits.
[src:derandomization/small-bias-sample-space] The probabilistic method gives a non-explicit construction that achieves size $s=O(n/\epsilon ^{2})$ .
[src:derandomization/small-bias-sample-space] The construction is non-explicit in the sense that finding the $\epsilon$ -biased set requires a lot of true randomness, which does not help towards the goal of reducing the overall randomness.
[src:derandomization/small-bias-sample-space] However, this non-explicit construction is useful because it shows that these efficient codes exist.
[src:derandomization/small-bias-sample-space] On the other hand, the best known lower bound for the size of $\epsilon$ -biased sets is $s=\Omega (n/(\epsilon ^{2}\log(1/\epsilon ))$ , that is, in order for a set to be $\epsilon$ -biased, it must be at least that big.
[src:derandomization/small-bias-sample-space] In particular, none of these constructions yields the smallest $\epsilon$ -biased sets for all settings of $\epsilon$ and n .
[src:derandomization/small-bias-sample-space] An important application of small-bias sets lies in the construction of almost k-wise independent sample spaces.
[src:derandomization/small-bias-sample-space] A random variable Y over $\{0,1\}^{n}$ is a *k-wise independent space* if, for all index sets $I\subseteq \{1,\dots ,n\}$ of size k , the marginal distribution $Y|_{I}$ is exactly equal to the uniform distribution over $\{0,1\}^{k}$ .
[src:derandomization/small-bias-sample-space] k-wise independent spaces are fairly well understood.
[src:derandomization/small-bias-sample-space] Joffe (1974) constructs a k -wise independent space Y over the finite field with some prime number $n>k$ of elements, i.e., Y is a distribution over $\mathbb {F} _{n}^{n}$ .
[src:derandomization/small-bias-sample-space] where the calculation is done in $\mathbb {F} _{n}$ .
[src:derandomization/small-bias-sample-space] Joffe (1974) proves that the distribution Y constructed in this way is k -wise independent as a distribution over $\mathbb {F} _{n}^{n}$ .
[src:derandomization/small-bias-sample-space] The distribution Y is uniform on its support, and hence, the support of Y forms a *k -wise independent set*.
[src:derandomization/small-bias-sample-space] It contains all $n^{k}$ strings in $\mathbb {F} _{n}^{k}$ that have been extended to strings of length n using the deterministic rule above.
[src:derandomization/small-bias-sample-space] Naor & Naor (1990) give a general framework for combining small k-wise independent spaces with small $\epsilon$ -biased spaces to obtain $\delta$ -almost k-wise independent spaces of even smaller size.
[src:derandomization/small-bias-sample-space] That is, when given a uniformly random input, the output of $G_{1}$ is a k-wise independent space, and the output of $G_{2}$ is $\epsilon$ -biased.
[src:derandomization/small-bias-sample-space] In order for G to yield a $\delta$ -almost k-wise independent space, we need to set $\epsilon =\delta 2^{-k/2}$ , which leads to a seed length of $\ell =\log \log n+O(k+\log(\delta ^{-1}))$ and a sample space of total size $2^{\ell }\leq \log n\cdot {\text{poly}}(2^{k}\cdot \delta ^{-1})$ .
